               <p>The indictment was opened by Mr. Chetwood as follows.</p>
               <p>My Lord and Gentlemen of the Jury, This is an indictment as you have heard against the gentleman at the bar, for wilfully and maliciously firing at Huxley Sandon, Esq; a loaded pistol: Gentlemen there is no attempt on the part of the prosecutor, to carry this further than the facts will go,<xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="178412080204"></xptr> therefore I shall only say in opening this case to you, that the prosecutor and the prisoner, had been for a long time in habits of friendship, the prisoner always had access to the house of the prosecutor, and they were in great friendship and intimacy; sometime since it was supposed the prisoner was going to France, or Italy, and he went to the house of the prosecutor, and prevailed on the wife of the prosecutor to accompany him to Dover, and accordingly she did accompany him to Dover; the prosecutor enraged and angry at that time, no doubt of it, pursued his wife and his friend to Dover, however they cluded the search, and came back to town: Information was given after several endeavours to find them, that they were at a Bagnio, in Long Acre, the prosecutor and his friends went to search there, they were denied, but the prosecutor and his friends had reason to think that they either were in the house, or coming to the house, as they had been in the house, and were very well known there, the man said at first they were not there, and he did not know them. However from several expressions, the prosecutor and his friends were convinced that they did know the prisoner, and in a little while after they heard the feet of two people walking, as if in great confusion over their heads, and they were then pretty well satisfied, that the prisoner at the bar was in the house, and was in company with Mrs. Sandon, who has been the unfortunate cause of this prosecution; Gentlemen, the prosecutor and his friends went up stairs, there they met a servant, coming out of a room with a candle in her hand, and one of the friends of the prosecutor took a candle from her, and they were going to enter the room, Mr. 
               <persName id="t17841208-194-person1720">
                  Sandon
               <interp inst="t17841208-194-person1720" type="given" value="Sandon"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17841208-194-person1720" type="gender" value="indeterminate"></interp>
                  </persName>
             the husband, was going in first, he was willing and desirous to be thoroughly satisfied, whether the prisoner and his wife were there or not, and immediately a pistol was fired by somebody; that it was loaded, was most certain, because the ball passed through a part of his hat, there was no light in the room at the time, but however, he saw by the firing of the pistol, that it was perhaps the prisoner at the bar, he was pretty positive at that time, however, they called fresh assistance and took the prisoner and Mrs. Sandon; the witnesses will inform you, in what situation they found the prisoner at the bar, and how they found Mrs. Sandon, I believe they were both armed at that time, Mrs. Sandon had pistols loaded in her hand, as well as the prisoner; whether or no, the prisoner was the person that fired the pistol at Mr. Sandon, it will be for you to enquire; there is little doubt, I should apprehend, that it will be proved to be him; if you find that he fired the pistol, you will have no difficulty in pronouncing him guilty of shooting, maliciously and feloniously, against Mr. Sandon: Gentlemen, we shall call our witnesses and prove the facts; and if you believe he was the person that fired the pistol at the prosecutor, you will find him guilty.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t17841208-194-person1721">
                  MARY
                   JONES
               <interp inst="t17841208-194-person1721" type="surname" value="JONES"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17841208-194-person1721" type="given" value="MARY"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17841208-194-person1721" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                  </persName>
             sworn.</p>
               <p>Examined by Mr. Chetwood. Where do you live? - At the Royal Hotel, in Long Acre.</p>
               <p>Did you live there in October last? - Yes?</p>
               <p>Did you ever see the prisoner at the bar? - Yes.</p>
               <p>Did you ever see him at that house? - Yes.</p>
               <p>Do you remember him there on the 24th of October, and do you remember Mr. Sandon, the prosecutor, coming to that house? - Yes.</p>
               <p>Was the prisoner in the house at that time? - No Sir, not when they came in first, he was out.</p>
               <p>Did he come in during the time Mr. Sandon was there? - Yes, and he went up stairs into the room.</p>
               <p>Who was with him? - A lady.</p>
               <p>Did you see Mr. Sandon go up stairs afterwards? - No, I was in the room with the Count, at the time they came up stairs.</p>
               <p>Did you come out of the room and see Mr. Sandon? - I came out of the room, but I do not recollect seeing Mr. Sandon; I was in the room, and the Lady said she<xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="178412080205"></xptr> would fire at the first person that came into the room, the bell rang in the room where the Count and the lady were, and I answered the bell.</p>
               <p>Were they armed? - The lady was, but I do not recollect seeing pistols in the Count's hands, I saw pistols in the lady's hands, the lady said she would fire at the first that came in, for she would sooner die than go with them.</p>
               <p>Did the lady mention any names, or had any been mentioned to her? - No Sir, she said she would kill the first that came in, she would fire at the first that came in, for she would sooner die, than go with them.</p>
               <p>(The Count desired a chair that he might sit down to take notes. A chair ordered.)</p>
               <p>When you came out of the room, did you leave any candle in the room? - I brought out the candle, and somebody took the candle, but who it was I cannot say, I did not stop a moment, I was frightened and came down stairs.</p>
               <p>Mr. Erskine, and Mr. Garrow, Prisoner's Council.</p>
               <p>Mr. Erskine. Pray my girl, had Mrs. 
               <persName id="t17841208-194-person1722">
                  Sandon
               <interp inst="t17841208-194-person1722" type="given" value="Sandon"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17841208-194-person1722" type="gender" value="indeterminate"></interp>
                  </persName>
             any more pistols than one? - She had two, I do not recollect the count had any, she was dressed in mens cloaths, and had a pistol in each hand.</p>
               <p>You are sure it was her, that said she would fire at the first man that came in? - Yes.</p>
               <p>What house is this? - The Royal Hotel, in Long Acre, I live there as a servant.</p>
               <p>Who is this house kept by? - By Mr. 
               <persName id="t17841208-194-person1723">
                  James
                   Soundy
               <interp inst="t17841208-194-person1723" type="surname" value="Soundy"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17841208-194-person1723" type="given" value="James"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17841208-194-person1723" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            , and 
               <persName id="t17841208-194-person1724">
                  John
                   Brewer
               <interp inst="t17841208-194-person1724" type="surname" value="Brewer"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17841208-194-person1724" type="given" value="John"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17841208-194-person1724" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            , they are partners.</p>
               <p>You are the servant? - Yes.</p>
               <p>What is Mr. Brewer's 
               <persName id="t17841208-194-person1725">
                  Christian
                   Name
               <interp inst="t17841208-194-person1725" type="surname" value="Name"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17841208-194-person1725" type="given" value="Christian"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17841208-194-person1725" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            ? - John.</p>
               <p>What is Mr. Sandy's Name? - 
               <persName id="t17841208-194-person1726">
                  James
                   Soundy
               <interp inst="t17841208-194-person1726" type="surname" value="Soundy"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17841208-194-person1726" type="given" value="James"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17841208-194-person1726" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            .</p>
               <p>Mr. Erskine. Then there is an end of it; my Lord, I submit here is a fatal variance on the indictment.</p>
               <p>Court to Mr. Chetwood. What do you say to this? - Mr. Chetwood, I submit it may be considered as surplusage.</p>
               <p>Mr. Erskine. It is too plain, it is A. B. C.</p>
               <p>Court. Gentlemen of the Jury, there can be no doubt at all in this case, they have taken upon themselves to state in the indictment, whose house it is; I do not know that it was necessary for them to have so done, but having done it, they are bound in point of law to prove it, and the evidence turns out that it is not the dwelling house of 
               <persName id="t17841208-194-person1727">
                  James
                   Brewer
               <interp inst="t17841208-194-person1727" type="surname" value="Brewer"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17841208-194-person1727" type="given" value="James"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17841208-194-person1727" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
             and 
               <persName id="t17841208-194-person1728">
                  John
                   Sandy
               <interp inst="t17841208-194-person1728" type="surname" value="Sandy"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17841208-194-person1728" type="given" value="John"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17841208-194-person1728" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            , but of 
               <persName id="t17841208-194-person1729">
                  James
                   Soundy
               <interp inst="t17841208-194-person1729" type="surname" value="Soundy"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17841208-194-person1729" type="given" value="James"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17841208-194-person1729" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
             and 
               <persName id="t17841208-194-person1730">
                  John
                   Brewer
               <interp inst="t17841208-194-person1730" type="surname" value="Brewer"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17841208-194-person1730" type="given" value="John"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17841208-194-person1730" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            , that is a fatal variance in the indictment, and where a man is charged on a capital offence, strict law is adhered to, so that you cannot do any thing but acquit him.</p>
               <p>
                  <rs id="t17841208-194-verdict867" type="verdictDescription">
                     <interp inst="t17841208-194-verdict867" type="verdictCategory" value="notGuilty"></interp>
               NOT GUILTY
            </rs>.</p>
               <p>Tried by the second Middlesex Jury before Mr. 
